Clean 2006 BMW X3 3.0I.  Beautiful and rare Blue Water Metallic exterior and tan interior color combination. 5-speed automatic transmission, AWD, CD/AM/FM radio, cold A/C (just serviced along w/oil change), alloy wheels, split rear-seats, driver/passenger air bags, multi-function remote w/ keyless entry, electric windows/door locks, cruise control, lighted vanity mirrors and many other extras.  Missing tow eye cover in rear (~$20 to replace), tires ~50% tread remaining and a few blemishes on the exterior (scuffs, scratches, normal wear & tear).  Would make an excellent, safe run-around town or college vehicle.  Title in hand, priced to sell!

2005 Ford F350 Lariat (Bullet Proofed). This truck was bullet proofed early on and has been well maintained. Truck is equiped with a 6.0 liter turbo diesel. Currently has 116K miles. Everything on the truck works as it should, truck is in excellent condition. Truck is in all original condition (except for the Bullet Proof upgrades). Truck comes equipped with gooseneck hitch, 15,000 lbs bumper hitch, brake controller, and upfitter switches. Has 430 limited slip gears. Fully loaded interior with heated leather power seats and power sliding back glass. It is an excellent choice for hauling a 5th wheel camper or for anyone needing to haul heavy loads. If you are looking for a pre-emission controlled diesel, you will not find a better truck than this one. Price is firm, Call Mark at  show contact info

Up for sale is my 1993 Chevy G20 Van. This van is in great running condition, and is very clean for it's age. I bought it in 2016 and have given it a full once-over. This one is the real deal. It has the 350ci V8, 4L60E transmission with tow package. This is a "2500" series heavy duty commercial van. Working front and rear AC/Heat. Electronic sofa / bed. Storage compartments, mood lights, all the standards for conversion vans of that era. The high top does not have skylights so this van has not had water damage and does not smell moldy like a lot of them do. The odometer reading is a little less than actual miles, due to it failing and being repaired a few thousand miles later. Actual miles on the van is approx 173k. Although not pictured, the middle captains chairs are included. Runs VERY smooth. Does not smoke at all. Shifts perfectly. I would easily trust this van for another cross country trip.  Here is some of the work that's recently been done to it. -Interior carpet removed and replaced with new carpet up front (black), and vinyl plank in the mid/rear. Interior upholstery steam cleaned. (all done in 2017) -New fuel pump 2017 (AC Delco) -New water pump 2019 (AC Delco) -New water hoses and heater hoses (2017) -New serpentine belt, spare included (2017) -New alternator 2017 -New plugs and distributor cap (delco) and wires (forgot the brand) -Rebuilt AC Compressor (2017) -New battery (2017) -New rear main seal (2017) -New brake rotors/calipers/hoses (2016/2017) -All new tires (2020) -New wiper blades (2020) -Pioneer cd player  Here is some info about the condition -Runs very well (just got done with a 6250 mile trip around the western US). -Most features work -I've made a point to change the oil/filter every 3000 miles. -I can provide paperwork for most of the work that I've done  Here are some of the issues it has -Front master cylinder needs replaced (I already have a spare. I may replace it, or may leave it up to the buyer.) -The brakes are the main issue that will need to be fixed on this van. -Minor body rust in a couple of places (although the van has been in the south for a long time, maybe it's whole life) -Wipers sometimes get "confused" as to which setting they're supposed to be on, but will always turn on / off. -Needs to have the wiper fluid reservoir connected (i have it) -Oil cooler lines bypassed with Melling oil filter adapter. OK if you're not towing. If you are, the hoses are easy and inexpensive to replace to reconnect to the oil cooler (i have the original adapter as well) -Very small transmission fluid leak off rear seal (common problem, very small) -Very small water leak from intake manifold gasket, front driver side -Small exhaust leak from right side header (small ticking sound when engine loaded, quiet during cruising) -Hole rusting in muffler toward the rear, causes the van to be a little louder than normal.  I live in Birmingham, AL, which is were this van is located. It has a clear Alabama title in my name. I'm listing it in several cities on the west coast, due to increased demand for vans in those areas. Buyer can drive it back, or we can arrange to have it shipped (approx $1800 or so) to the west coast.  Please feel free to contact me via the craigslist email and then we can talk on the phone if you're a serious buyer.

Regretfully selling the most fun car I've ever owned.  I am the second owner and bought the car in late 2017 with only 2700 miles on it.  Now has just under 25k miles.  Clean title.  Never had any issues.  No accidents.  Adult driven, never raced.  Used mainly as a commuter.  I have logged all maintenance data.  MSRP with options was over $32k.      Cool fact: The TRD wheels and exhaust were port-installed before it reached the dealership.  Does have factory navigation.  Has OEM rubber floor mats with the 86 logo.  Also have an OEM trunk mat with the 86 logo.  I replaced the tires with fresh Continental DWS06 this summer, so those have little mileage on them.  Other things to note, I've changed the differential and transmission oil twice already with Motul 300.  I've changed the engine oil every 5000 miles, currently using Pennzoil Platinum 0W20.  Just recently did the clutch fluid and brake fluid. Also completed a clay bar, polish, and paint sealant treatment this fall.  I've taken only the best care of this car.  It needs nothing but a skilled driver.  Here are the subtle but effective modifications I've made:  Whiteline rear subframe bushings Whiteline differential bushings Whiteline transmission mount insert Perrin transmission support mount Perrin shifter mount bushing MTEC shifter springs MTEC clutch spring MTEC clutch line Racer X oil catch can Racer X sound tube delete Racer X reverse lockout Grimmspeed drop in air filter  I have all original parts, so you could make the car 100% stock again if you chose to do so, but why?  These mods have made the car come alive, and it is so direct.  It feels special.    If you are interested, feel free to reach me by phone or email.  I'm happy to show the car, but to serious buyers only who know how to drive a manual.

Small Motor Home / Class B advantages why look closely at the Transit Connect Campervan?:  1. Better fuel economy  2. Camper vans are easier to drive than a big motorhome  3. Can go through any car wash- easy to keep clean inside and outside clean- smaller is better  4. Can access smaller roads and dirt roads leading to "out of the way" dispersed camping opportunities  5. Can take a nap, get some sleep rest wherever parking is allowed.  6. With a small RV you can and drive your vehicle to explore the area and your RV home and food is always with you so you can save on restaurant meals. With a larger RV you would need to leave it behind and take a second- pulled behind vehicle to enable parking and exploring  7. A camper van will go anywhere a car can go- garage, parking garage, small roads, parking in busy cities or high brush areas with low trees.  8. If, while exploring, you find a great overnight spot, you can stay without having to backtrack to get your RV.  9. Storage is enough for most people, with less storage space you tend to bring less "stuff" you will likely not use and be less tempted to buy too much in route. Extra stuff along the way on an extended trip gets mailed home enabling you to stay on the road without clutter  10. Can be used as a primary or secondary vehicle when not traveling. Great for tailgating.  11. This small Camper Van RV should hold its value better than a larger RV due to escalating fuel prices, high storage prices and higher insurance costs for the bigger RV motorhomes.  12. You don't need a toad (tow vehicle) adding additional expense and set up time when camping and maneuvering around your destination  13. You can park it in your driveway- big plus, no storage fee's  14. You will not pull into a parking lot wondering if you will be able to park or turn around  15. More camping opportunities, many camp grounds do not have spots for the larger motorhomes  16. Great for a trip to your friend's bon-fire and parties- You always have a place to stay without imposing on their home and space. Beside the big benefit of sleeping in your own bed with your own bedding!  17. Of course you save on hotel fees when traveling but with a Transit Connect Camper van you can pull over, sleep and not have to unload to go into a hotel, pack back up and load vehicle again each night. Setting the bed up takes seconds!  18. Using a camper van as a primary vehicle is a wonderful option- less insurance, less cost maintaining multiple vehicles and you can be spontaneous- your gear is with you, spend the night, make a meal, go for that extended hike. Take advantage of your time without having to return home to resupply for your next adventure.  19. A Large Motor home often does not get used many days out of the year. Think about "cost per use when making your RV purchase decision!  Large home= monthly payment + storage when not in use, + 8 +/- MPG fuel economy, + insurance, + depreciation, + cleaning and maintenance costs, plus higher camp ground fees- full hookups) Consider a $100,000 big Motorhome RV financed with all associated costs that is used 3 weeks per year on average. You will find this RV costing over $1050 per use!  Small Motor home= Higher use, Reduced monthly payment, high MPG fuel economy, less insurance cost (insures like a car), will likely depreciate less, easier to sell if you choose to sell later, clean at home or at gas station car wash, lower camp fees.  NOTE: You must run your own numbers when considering the examples above. 1) Financing 2) how often you use your RV 3) style of camping and other variables will all make a difference in your cost per use.
